WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.540
All right, now it's good afternoon.

00:00:09.540 --> 00:00:15.320
So if you were coming here expecting to hear Greg Wilson, who is a well-known educator,

00:00:15.320 --> 00:00:22.240
talk about the future of data science education in 2022, you're going to be disappointed.

00:00:22.240 --> 00:00:26.200
Because he wrote the abstract for this talk, and then he talked to me and said, you're

00:00:26.200 --> 00:00:28.940
going to have to give it.

00:00:28.940 --> 00:00:34.060
So my name is Carl Howe, I'm the Director of Education for RStudio, and I'm very honored

00:00:34.060 --> 00:00:36.939
to be here to talk to so many wonderful people.

00:00:36.939 --> 00:00:41.980
If you want to know a little bit more about me, I actually have a very old and decrepit

00:00:41.980 --> 00:00:47.820
website at carlhowe.com, but it does have my full resume.

00:00:47.820 --> 00:00:51.259
One of the things you should know is this is my third career.

00:00:51.259 --> 00:00:56.759
I started my life as a software engineer, I have a degree in computer science.

00:00:56.759 --> 00:00:59.599
Then I became an analyst.

00:00:59.599 --> 00:01:03.680
I don't know how you feel about analysts, I was an industry analyst, and one of my jobs

00:01:03.680 --> 00:01:07.279
was to predict the future.

00:01:07.279 --> 00:01:12.779
And I love this quote that came from a Danish parliamentarian, which is that it's difficult

00:01:12.779 --> 00:01:18.559
to make predictions, especially about the future.

00:01:18.559 --> 00:01:22.919
But I actually thrived in that business for about 20 years before I became the Director

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:24.000
of Education here.

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:29.199
I actually did also travel around the world teaching big data before I came here.

00:01:29.199 --> 00:01:32.879
But the thing that drew me here was RStudio's mission.

00:01:32.879 --> 00:01:36.680
And you heard it from JJ this morning, but I think it's worth repeating.

00:01:36.680 --> 00:01:44.160
We want to equip everyone, regardless of means, to participate in a global economy that rewards

00:01:44.160 --> 00:01:46.000
data literacy.

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:51.839
And one of the ways we're doing that is we have become a public benefit corporation.

00:01:51.839 --> 00:01:54.199
We think this is incredibly important.

00:01:54.199 --> 00:01:59.239
We want these tools to be around for hundreds of years.

00:01:59.239 --> 00:02:04.199
And we're willing to play the long game, to work hard to do this.

00:02:04.199 --> 00:02:09.139
Now when I joined, I decided we needed to have a mission in our education group as well.

00:02:09.139 --> 00:02:13.240
And by the way, when I say our education group, there's a variety of people, Greg is on the

00:02:13.240 --> 00:02:18.800
education group, Alison Hill, Garrett Grohleman, who's not able to be here because he's on

00:02:18.800 --> 00:02:20.080
family leave.

00:02:20.080 --> 00:02:24.520
But we also include people like Hadley Wickham, Jenny Bryan, all the folks in the Tidyverse

00:02:24.520 --> 00:02:25.520
team.

00:02:25.520 --> 00:02:26.720
So it's a great group.

00:02:26.720 --> 00:02:32.320
But we established a mission, which is we want to train the next million R users.

00:02:32.320 --> 00:02:36.320
Actually we did a hashtag and a talk last year about this.

00:02:36.320 --> 00:02:40.479
And you can actually use that hashtag to tweet about it.

00:02:40.479 --> 00:02:44.479
So let me talk a little bit about some of the things we've done to get there.

00:02:44.479 --> 00:02:51.160
Greg has actually headed up a group that is also our certified RStudio instructor team.

00:02:51.160 --> 00:02:53.520
We have nearly 100 certified instructors already.

00:02:53.520 --> 00:02:55.360
I'm just showing you some of the pictures.

00:02:55.360 --> 00:02:59.800
I don't expect you'll actually be able to recognize anyone.

00:02:59.800 --> 00:03:04.800
But here at RStudioConf, I think this has been incredibly exciting for me, that we have

00:03:04.800 --> 00:03:13.639
held 19 workshops here, led by a teaching staff of over 100, and teaching 1,300 students

00:03:13.800 --> 00:03:15.440
on Monday and Tuesday this week.

00:03:15.440 --> 00:03:22.160
I believe, and I'm happy to take contrary views, that this is the largest R education

00:03:22.160 --> 00:03:24.240
event in the world.

00:03:24.240 --> 00:03:27.080
And in addition to this, we also have other contributions.

00:03:27.080 --> 00:03:32.399
Many of you have seen our free online books, our packages for education, open source materials

00:03:32.399 --> 00:03:37.320
on GitHub, free academic licenses for RStudio Pro products.

00:03:37.320 --> 00:03:42.919
If you're an academic using our products for teaching, you get free licenses.

00:03:42.919 --> 00:03:47.080
And our annual survey of how people actually learn R.

00:03:47.080 --> 00:03:49.399
So we're doing a lot.

00:03:49.399 --> 00:03:52.720
But I'm sad to say, it's not nearly enough.

00:03:52.720 --> 00:03:54.199
We need to do more.

00:03:54.199 --> 00:03:58.880
And the reason is that when we survey our users, we discover something important, which

00:03:58.880 --> 00:04:01.520
is that most R users are self-taught.

00:04:01.520 --> 00:04:06.600
48%, almost half, are self-taught.

00:04:06.600 --> 00:04:13.279
Which means no matter how wonderful an instructor I am, I'm not reaching most of the world.

00:04:13.279 --> 00:04:20.359
And one of the challenges I see is that data science faces serious challenges in the next

00:04:20.359 --> 00:04:21.359
two years.

00:04:21.359 --> 00:04:26.160
You know, you would think, two years from now, it's within our vision.

00:04:26.160 --> 00:04:28.200
It's right on the horizon.

00:04:28.200 --> 00:04:31.519
But I think there are some big changes coming.

00:04:31.519 --> 00:04:36.200
And in the immortal words of Yoda, if you're not afraid, you will be.

00:04:36.200 --> 00:04:41.279
So I'm going to go through three challenges to guide you through this.

00:04:41.279 --> 00:04:44.959
The first is the data explosion.

00:04:44.959 --> 00:04:49.040
Frankly, we're drowning in data nowadays.

00:04:49.040 --> 00:04:56.320
I'm going to use just a really simple metric from IBM that said 90% of the data in the

00:04:56.320 --> 00:05:00.119
world was created in the last two years.

00:05:00.720 --> 00:05:02.760
90%.

00:05:02.760 --> 00:05:09.760
So if you think of data science as looking for a needle in a haystack, we have a problem.

00:05:09.760 --> 00:05:15.040
Because if we're looking for a needle in a haystack today, we're going to be looking

00:05:15.040 --> 00:05:18.920
at 10 haystacks by 2022.

00:05:18.920 --> 00:05:24.239
And by the way, by the time we get to 2024, we'll have 100 haystacks.

00:05:24.239 --> 00:05:27.760
Now I know most of you sort of say, oh, but computers get faster.

00:05:27.760 --> 00:05:30.040
It's no big deal.

00:05:30.040 --> 00:05:33.640
Moore's law isn't going to bail us out.

00:05:33.640 --> 00:05:35.200
This is Moore's law.

00:05:35.200 --> 00:05:38.679
Factor of two increase in computing power every 18 months.

00:05:38.679 --> 00:05:44.399
Actually originally a marketing campaign done by Intel, but it's worked out pretty well.

00:05:44.399 --> 00:05:47.200
This is the data explosion.

00:05:47.200 --> 00:05:52.839
If we look out five years, Moore's law gives us a factor of about four and a half in terms

00:05:52.839 --> 00:05:55.160
of computing power.

00:05:55.239 --> 00:06:00.959
The data explosion, we're going to have 46 times as much data in five years.

00:06:00.959 --> 00:06:06.799
So we're drowning in data, and we're not really prepared to process it.

00:06:06.799 --> 00:06:11.399
Secondly, I want to talk about something that I really don't have to explain to you, but

00:06:11.399 --> 00:06:15.959
it's such a great topic, and it's something we really have to pay attention to.

00:06:15.959 --> 00:06:19.160
It's irreproducibility results.

00:06:19.160 --> 00:06:22.839
Sorry, I can't even say the word.

00:06:22.839 --> 00:06:24.160
Unreproducible results.

00:06:24.160 --> 00:06:26.679
We no longer trust science.

00:06:26.679 --> 00:06:32.760
This is a real issue, and it's not because science is inherently untrustworthy.

00:06:32.760 --> 00:06:35.399
It's that we're kind of screwing up how we do it.

00:06:35.399 --> 00:06:38.359
There's a great article in Physics Today.

00:06:38.359 --> 00:06:43.440
By the way, I'm borrowing from Gerrit Grohlmann's slides here, because they're just so compelling.

00:06:43.440 --> 00:06:49.880
He heard about this study that was being done about supercooled water published in Physics

00:06:49.880 --> 00:06:51.559
Today.

00:06:51.559 --> 00:06:52.559
They published the paper.

00:06:52.559 --> 00:06:57.600
They were basically just cooling down water, it had to be very clean water, and passed

00:06:57.600 --> 00:07:01.760
the point of freezing down to very, very low temperatures.

00:07:01.760 --> 00:07:07.440
Two labs ran the same experiment, and they got different results.

00:07:07.440 --> 00:07:13.480
After seven years of suing companies like Nature, I think it was published ... No, it's

00:07:13.480 --> 00:07:15.559
in Physics Today, of course.

00:07:15.559 --> 00:07:19.720
After suing the publisher, they finally got access to the other team's data.

00:07:20.559 --> 00:07:26.040
What they discovered was there was a bug in the code that caused their studies to diverge.

00:07:26.040 --> 00:07:31.000
You can blame this as just one isolated institute, but there's a famous Amgen study that was

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:38.399
done in 2012 that discovered that when they looked at landmark results, the foundations

00:07:38.399 --> 00:07:46.799
of their very science, they could reproduce only six out of 53.

00:07:46.799 --> 00:07:50.160
Six out of 53.

00:07:50.160 --> 00:07:52.040
Let's not just blame the farm industry.

00:07:52.040 --> 00:07:53.600
This is everywhere.

00:07:53.600 --> 00:08:00.640
If you look in the field of psychology, for example, they're only able to reproduce 36

00:08:00.640 --> 00:08:05.000
out of 100 important psychology studies.

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:10.160
If we look at economics, it's the same story, 29 out of 59.

00:08:10.160 --> 00:08:17.679
Look at Nature and Science, the two premier publications in the scientific world, 13 of

00:08:17.679 --> 00:08:19.160
21.

00:08:19.160 --> 00:08:22.799
By the way, if you want the references, they're right here.

00:08:22.799 --> 00:08:25.839
I did some very serious research on this.

00:08:25.839 --> 00:08:27.519
I worked very hard on it.

00:08:27.519 --> 00:08:35.559
I did 21 coin tosses and ended up with 12 heads.

00:08:35.559 --> 00:08:43.159
If you look at the ratios there, economics is doing less well than the coin tosses and

00:08:43.159 --> 00:08:46.159
Nature and Science are only just barely doing better.

00:08:46.159 --> 00:08:50.520
Needless to say, this has caused a few headlines.

00:08:50.520 --> 00:08:58.919
It ranges from the New York Times to the Atlantic and to the Wall Street Journal.

00:08:58.919 --> 00:09:02.559
I just want to try to put this in perspective.

00:09:02.559 --> 00:09:08.679
In the United States, so not the world, in the United States, the cost to the biomedical

00:09:08.679 --> 00:09:18.080
industry in the United States for irreproducible research is estimated to be about $28 billion.

00:09:18.080 --> 00:09:23.799
Just to put $28 billion in perspective, that's enough money to buy a latte for everyone

00:09:23.799 --> 00:09:30.679
on earth from Starbucks.

00:09:30.679 --> 00:09:36.780
Or if you like, it might be a little bit more fun if we just simply say, I can buy everyone

00:09:36.780 --> 00:09:44.619
in this room with this money your own island in the Bahamas while supplies last.

00:09:44.619 --> 00:09:46.000
This is a serious issue.

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:50.239
That's just in the United States and that's just in the biomedical industry.

00:09:50.239 --> 00:09:53.119
It's trillions of dollars worldwide.

00:09:53.119 --> 00:09:56.119
So this is a real thing.

00:09:56.119 --> 00:10:00.559
Unreproducible results is something we're going to have to address in data science education.

00:10:00.559 --> 00:10:05.599
All right, the third one is I think, I'm not sure how many people are going to see this

00:10:05.599 --> 00:10:07.039
one coming.

00:10:07.039 --> 00:10:09.400
It's fake data.

00:10:09.400 --> 00:10:13.539
Data has just become another way to lie.

00:10:13.539 --> 00:10:17.739
If you look at the headlines, you see this every day.

00:10:17.739 --> 00:10:23.539
We had the Brexit issue where they were promised there was going to be 350 million pounds for

00:10:23.539 --> 00:10:25.219
the NHS.

00:10:25.219 --> 00:10:27.099
That's not happening.

00:10:27.099 --> 00:10:32.179
Hundreds of climate skeptics have convinced an international campaign to get rid of the

00:10:32.179 --> 00:10:38.739
net zero targets and there are people donating millions to anti-vaxxers.

00:10:38.739 --> 00:10:41.619
Now I blame this really on media explosion.

00:10:41.700 --> 00:10:45.059
We get overwhelmed with media everywhere we go.

00:10:45.059 --> 00:10:50.659
It didn't used to be the case that you would get the latest headlines on your person within

00:10:50.659 --> 00:10:53.020
seconds of them being published.

00:10:53.020 --> 00:10:56.239
So the world has sped up, we're overwhelmed with media.

00:10:56.239 --> 00:10:58.340
So what do we do?

00:10:58.340 --> 00:11:03.299
When people are overwhelmed with media, they turn to their trusted sources.

00:11:03.299 --> 00:11:07.780
The most trusted people in the United States or in the world even, they are people like

00:11:08.739 --> 00:11:12.419
Facebook, Google, and Twitter.

00:11:12.419 --> 00:11:16.719
They're relying on their friends for their facts.

00:11:16.719 --> 00:11:21.140
The Royal Society of Open Science has actually published a paper on this called Fake Science

00:11:21.140 --> 00:11:25.059
and the Knowledge Crisis, Ignorance Can Be Fatal.

00:11:25.059 --> 00:11:29.539
And the real danger was actually illustrated very well by the television series Chernobyl.

00:11:29.539 --> 00:11:35.539
The real danger is if we hear enough lies, we no longer recognize the truth when we see

00:11:35.539 --> 00:11:37.539
it.

00:11:37.539 --> 00:11:41.739
Now I'm going to illustrate this with a true life example.

00:11:41.739 --> 00:11:44.380
And some of you probably know this, it's a very famous study.

00:11:44.380 --> 00:11:46.380
It's called the Rogoff-Reinhart model.

00:11:46.380 --> 00:11:48.099
Anybody heard of this before?

00:11:48.099 --> 00:11:50.580
Yeah, a bunch of you.

00:11:50.580 --> 00:11:55.859
This was published in 2010, I believe, and the conclusion is very simple.

00:11:55.859 --> 00:11:59.900
Two Harvard professors published a report that said when a country owes more than 90%

00:11:59.900 --> 00:12:03.500
of its GDP, it slides into recession.

00:12:03.500 --> 00:12:07.219
And they had done studies and models and they were very proud of this.

00:12:07.900 --> 00:12:12.500
And this was the foundation for austerity in Europe for the next 10 years.

00:12:12.500 --> 00:12:19.460
Well, it turns out that some folks at University of Amherst said, well, this is a great study.

00:12:19.460 --> 00:12:22.659
It's the sort of thing I can give to a graduate student to reproduce.

00:12:22.659 --> 00:12:27.700
So a fellow by the name of Thomas Herndon took this data and discovered a small problem.

00:12:27.700 --> 00:12:29.460
He actually talked to the Harvard professors.

00:12:29.460 --> 00:12:32.780
They gave him their very detailed Excel spreadsheet.

00:12:32.780 --> 00:12:36.140
And when he looked at it, he saw this.

00:12:36.140 --> 00:12:41.179
Over on the right hand of that table, there's a little selection there.

00:12:41.179 --> 00:12:45.219
If you notice, it doesn't cover all the countries in the list.

00:12:45.219 --> 00:12:49.580
They missed five countries at the bottom.

00:12:49.580 --> 00:12:54.059
And so they've just been dragging this column across the spreadsheet and they missed these

00:12:54.059 --> 00:12:55.099
five countries.

00:12:55.099 --> 00:12:59.619
If you include the five countries, their conclusion is completely different.

00:12:59.619 --> 00:13:05.580
There is no implied descent into recession.

00:13:05.580 --> 00:13:12.059
Rogoff and Reinhart's results weren't reproducible, yet they led to this.

00:13:12.059 --> 00:13:19.260
They led to the cutoff of a lot of medical care, provisions for the poor, because the

00:13:19.260 --> 00:13:24.859
claim was that Greece couldn't afford it, and Britain for that matter.

00:13:24.859 --> 00:13:27.619
All right, so let me finish up here.

00:13:27.619 --> 00:13:29.900
We do see some hope.

00:13:29.900 --> 00:13:33.659
And I just want to say, one of the things about analysts is they're just somebody who

00:13:33.659 --> 00:13:37.940
reports the obvious, preferably before someone else does.

00:13:37.940 --> 00:13:41.020
So I'm just going to finish up with, here's what we need to be doing.

00:13:41.020 --> 00:13:46.500
We need to focus on teaching data science, not coding science.

00:13:46.500 --> 00:13:47.500
So we've got some challenges.

00:13:47.500 --> 00:13:51.320
So over on the left hand side, let's talk about the changes we need.

00:13:51.320 --> 00:13:53.260
And this one's going to be real obvious.

00:13:53.260 --> 00:13:55.340
We're going to embrace statistics.

00:13:55.340 --> 00:13:59.179
Data science embraces statistics on real data.

00:13:59.179 --> 00:14:00.559
Why?

00:14:00.559 --> 00:14:03.979
Because when the data gets really big, you can no longer process all of it, which means

00:14:03.979 --> 00:14:06.179
you're going to have to do sampling.

00:14:06.179 --> 00:14:08.099
That requires statistics.

00:14:08.099 --> 00:14:09.780
Why real data?

00:14:09.780 --> 00:14:12.539
Because real world stuff is just messy.

00:14:12.539 --> 00:14:15.780
If you don't know how to deal with it, you're not going to be able to do data science well.

00:14:15.780 --> 00:14:20.380
There's a wonderful book coming out from Janine Harris at Washington University in St. Louis

00:14:20.380 --> 00:14:23.859
called Statistics with R. I've only gotten a preview of it.

00:14:23.859 --> 00:14:30.400
But this is a wonderful narration, a wonderful story of dealing with real world data sets

00:14:30.400 --> 00:14:33.900
using R. My second point is we're going to have to

00:14:33.900 --> 00:14:35.979
use public processes.

00:14:35.979 --> 00:14:42.780
And here, good data science relies on R Markdown computational documents and open processes.

00:14:42.780 --> 00:14:45.200
All of you are probably pretty familiar with R Markdown.

00:14:45.200 --> 00:14:46.200
We love it.

00:14:46.200 --> 00:14:50.219
But I don't think people have really understood the huge impact of being able to take our

00:14:50.219 --> 00:14:57.219
process for doing science, documenting it, and creating papers that we don't read.

00:14:57.219 --> 00:14:59.419
They're papers that we run.

00:14:59.419 --> 00:15:01.460
But we're going to need a few other things.

00:15:01.460 --> 00:15:06.299
We're going to need curated data so that we can trust the data we work with.

00:15:06.299 --> 00:15:08.340
We're going to need computational documents.

00:15:08.340 --> 00:15:09.760
Those are pretty easy.

00:15:09.760 --> 00:15:15.059
But we also need open source publishing of sources to allow others to run our work.

00:15:15.059 --> 00:15:19.380
I'm just going to wind up here with the fourth point, which is fake data.

00:15:19.380 --> 00:15:21.460
How do we combat fake data?

00:15:21.460 --> 00:15:25.099
Well, we need authoritative storytellers.

00:15:25.099 --> 00:15:26.820
We have to democratize data science.

00:15:26.820 --> 00:15:30.619
And here I'm going to just do a shout out to a few organizations and people.

00:15:30.619 --> 00:15:39.539
I'm going to start with R Ladies.

00:15:39.539 --> 00:15:44.659
Probably the most amazing organization for democratizing data science in the world.

00:15:44.659 --> 00:15:49.059
They got together and they said, let's take the data science to the experts.

00:15:49.059 --> 00:15:50.859
The women who are working in these industries.

00:15:50.859 --> 00:15:52.419
And by the way, it's not just women.

00:15:52.419 --> 00:15:53.419
It's everyone.

00:15:53.419 --> 00:15:57.239
But they found a way to really engage a new audience.

00:15:57.239 --> 00:16:01.659
But our democratized experts must be viral storytellers.

00:16:01.659 --> 00:16:04.020
And here I'm going to ask you a question.

00:16:04.020 --> 00:16:06.619
Who would you trust more to diagnose your illness?

00:16:06.619 --> 00:16:12.840
A data scientist who learned some medicine or a doctor who learned some data science?

00:16:12.840 --> 00:16:14.380
Anybody going for number one?

00:16:14.380 --> 00:16:15.380
Okay.

00:16:15.380 --> 00:16:18.659
Well, here I want to give a shout out to Stephen Kaduke.

00:16:18.659 --> 00:16:22.900
He's an MD and PhD at the Children's Hospital of Philadelphia.

00:16:22.900 --> 00:16:27.419
And he has created a program for doctors to teach doctors.

00:16:27.419 --> 00:16:29.820
They don't want to hear from nurses or other folks.

00:16:29.820 --> 00:16:31.479
They want to learn from doctors.

00:16:31.479 --> 00:16:34.739
And he's promoting R to do that.

00:16:34.739 --> 00:16:37.880
Another person I'm going to give a shout out to is Desiree De Leon.

00:16:37.880 --> 00:16:42.179
And you're going to hear from her later.

00:16:42.179 --> 00:16:43.659
She's a fabulous person.

00:16:43.659 --> 00:16:46.739
And I'm not going to say anything about that because she's talking.

00:16:46.820 --> 00:16:50.820
And the final person I want to talk to is a farmer.

00:16:50.820 --> 00:16:56.099
A farmer who is sitting in my R Markdown and Interactive Dashboards course on Monday and

00:16:56.099 --> 00:16:57.099
Tuesday.

00:16:57.099 --> 00:16:58.380
He's from Brazil.

00:16:58.380 --> 00:17:03.340
He came here to learn how to create interactive dashboards so he could help other Brazilian

00:17:03.340 --> 00:17:07.099
farmers do farming better.

00:17:07.099 --> 00:17:09.260
So those are our challenges.

00:17:09.260 --> 00:17:14.739
We need to focus on teaching data science and not coding science.

00:17:14.739 --> 00:17:18.140
And it's really too soon to tell whether this is going to be successful.

00:17:18.140 --> 00:17:22.819
But with your help, each of you can help us overcome the new challenges in data science

00:17:22.819 --> 00:17:29.020
education and help everyone, regardless of means, participate in a global economy that

00:17:29.020 --> 00:17:31.180
rewards data literacy.

00:17:31.180 --> 00:17:34.180
Thank you so much.

00:17:34.180 --> 00:17:42.260
Okay, Carl, we've got time for a couple of questions.

00:17:42.260 --> 00:17:43.260
Wow.

00:17:43.260 --> 00:17:48.780
First one is, how do you see traditional schools and traditional curriculum fitting into all

00:17:48.780 --> 00:17:49.780
of this?

00:17:49.780 --> 00:17:50.780
Yeah.

00:17:50.780 --> 00:17:54.859
Well, there's a lot of ways we could work that.

00:17:54.859 --> 00:18:01.339
But one thing I see is that data science is going to go more broadly.

00:18:01.339 --> 00:18:04.339
The tier one colleges don't need our help.

00:18:04.339 --> 00:18:06.699
Community colleges, heck yeah.

00:18:06.699 --> 00:18:11.859
We need a lot more democratization to the community colleges is one thing.

00:18:11.859 --> 00:18:17.060
I'm working with a bunch of groups, including the Concord Consortium, on pushing down statistics

00:18:17.060 --> 00:18:21.819
and specifically learning statistics with R into high schools.

00:18:21.819 --> 00:18:25.140
Big problem with high schools, by the way, is their curriculum is already full.

00:18:25.140 --> 00:18:26.739
So a lot of this is extracurricular.

00:18:26.739 --> 00:18:31.339
But a lot of new curricula are coming out of these organizations that address high schools.

00:18:31.339 --> 00:18:34.859
And the other one is, you gave a good shout out to our ladies.

00:18:34.859 --> 00:18:39.780
Are there any other organizations that you think people ought to be putting their attention

00:18:39.780 --> 00:18:42.619
to that may not be as famous yet?

00:18:42.619 --> 00:18:46.540
Our OpenSci, I think, is a great one.

00:18:46.540 --> 00:18:47.540
Any others?

00:18:47.540 --> 00:18:49.739
Actually, you're probably better at that than I am.

00:18:49.739 --> 00:18:51.500
I haven't met everyone yet.

00:18:51.500 --> 00:18:53.699
I'm working on it, though.

00:18:53.699 --> 00:18:54.699
It's a big planet.

00:18:54.699 --> 00:18:55.699
That's true.

00:18:55.699 --> 00:18:56.699
Danny.

00:18:56.699 --> 00:18:57.699
Awesome.

00:18:57.699 --> 00:18:58.699
Yep.

00:18:58.699 --> 00:18:59.699
There's a more comprehensive approach.

00:18:59.699 --> 00:19:23.420
Okay.

00:19:23.420 --> 00:19:28.219
There's an organization called StatPrep, statprep.org.

00:19:28.219 --> 00:19:29.219
Okay.

00:19:29.219 --> 00:19:30.219
Thank you very much.

00:19:30.219 --> 00:19:32.699
Another round, please, for Carl, and we'll get our next speaker up.

